      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Richardson extrapolation-based GCI reported for hemolysis QoI on three systematically refined meshes; GCI below 5%.",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study completed; GCI for pressure-rise is 2.1%. GCI for hemolysis index is 11.4%, exceeding the 5% threshold. Near-blade boundary layer resolution remains insufficient at MRL 5 requirements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental boundary conditions documented with uncertainty bounds; inlet flow waveform, fluid temperature, and hematocrit matched to COU operating envelope within stated tolerances.",
      "rationale": "Inlet flow rate documented but hematocrit and fluid temperature during in-vitro experiments were not continuously monitored. Reported as nominal values only, introducing unquantified experimental uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative metric (e.g., E-metric or MAPE) applied to hemolysis QoI; comparison includes uncertainty intervals from both simulation and experiment.",
      "rationale": "Qualitative agreement reported for flow field. Quantitative comparison for hemolysis index limited to mean values without propagated experimental uncertainty; confidence intervals not overlapping at two of five operating points."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoI directly maps to clinical hemolysis threshold; sensitivity of predicted hemolysis to all major model parameters documented.",
      "rationale": "Normalized index of hemolysis is clinically relevant. However, the power-law exponent selection for the hemolysis model is based on literature values not specific to the blood formulation used in the COU; parameter relevance gap persists."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
